Introduction

Brief introduction into the Bella App IS a women’s health and wellness platform that tracks user activity, sleep, stress, and menstrual cycles to provide personalized health insights and guidance. It syncs with Bellabeat’s smart devices, like the Ivy, Leaf, and Time, to gather biometric data and offers features such as cycle tracking, pregnancy support, guided meditations, and personalized workout and nutrition plans through a premium membership. Core features Activity tracking: The app logs your daily movement and exercise based on data from Bellabeat devices like the Ivy and Leaf. Sleep tracking: When wearing a Bellabeat tracker, the app monitors your sleep patterns, including time spent in light and deep sleep. Menstrual and reproductive health tracking: A key feature is the ability to track your menstrual cycle, fertile days, and ovulation. A dedicated app, IVY Period & Pregnancy Tracker, also provides detailed reproductive health insights. Hydration tracking: If synced with a Bellabeat Spring smart water bottle, the app tracks your water intake and can send reminders to help you stay hydrated. Mindfulness and stress management: The app offers guided meditations and breathing exercises to help users reduce stress. Pregnancy tracking: For pregnant users, the app can be used to track fetal kicks and provides a prenatal calendar with information on baby development. Why are these features important valuable proposition of the product? The various features of the Bellabeat app form a compelling value proposition by specifically addressing the holistic health needs and concerns of women. The product differentiates itself from competitors by integrating health metrics with the female body and cycle, offering a personalized and empowering experience.

ASK

Business Task

The purpose of this analysis is to explore and analyze Fitbit fitness tracker data to identify patterns in users’ daily activity, distance covered, and calories expenditure, by the usage of these parameters, Bellabeat can:

Gain insights into user lifestyle habits (steps, distance, calories, and weekly/daily trends).

Identify opportunities to enhance the Bella App by following and replicating popular features in the fitbit app.

Provide fitness advice and recommendations which is user specific in order to improve health, activity, and wellness outcomes.

By Observing and analyzing the fitbit app it can give key insights where the Bella app can improve and develope their own total all in one women specific fitness lifestyle device S

Summary of Data Analysis

This report summarizes and analyses data collected from FitBit Fitness Tracker Data which was retrieved from Kaggle website click here [link] (https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/arashnic/fitbit).

The area of observations/ analysis goes as following

Steps taken analysis aims:

  • To determine the minimum, maximum, mean values of daily steps recorded by the fitbit device
  • To identify the number and percentage of users whose daily recorded steps exceed and less than that of average steps taken value,
  • To determine which day of the week has most and least recorded steps taken on the device
  • To determine which week of weekly data has the highest and lowest amount of recorded steps taken by the fitbit device
  • To determine which users are most and least active than others by tracking the user IDs with highest and lowest recorded total steps

Distance analysis aims

  • To determine the minimum, maximum, mean values of distance covered recorded by the fitbit device
  • To identify the number and percentage of users whose daily recorded distance covered exceed and less than that of average distance covered ,
  • To determine which day of the week has most recorded and least distance covered on the device
  • To determine which week of weekly data has the highest and lowest amount of recorded distance covered fitbit device
  • To determine which users are most and least active than others,by tracking the user IDs with highest and lowest distance covered

Calories used analysis aims

  • To determine the minimum, maximum, mean values of calories used recorded by the fitbit device
  • To identify the number and percentage of users whose daily recorded distance covered exceed and less than that of average calories used
  • To determine which day of the week has most recorded and least calories used on the device
  • To determine which week of weekly data has the highest and lowest amount of recorded calories used by fitbit device
  • To determine which users used up the most and least calories

Calculating weekly averages for calories expenditure for fitbit app users for the one month cycle

weekly_avg_calories <- archive %>% filter(Calories > 0) %>% + mutate(week = floor_date(ActivityDate, unit = “week”)) %>% group_by(week) %>% + summarise(average_weekly_calories = mean(Calories, na.rm = TRUE)) %>% arrange(week)
